附加记录：    

This sentence leads me to believe that the going theory is that 1483 was populated by organisms from our Earth (Baseline). Okay.

A few tens of thousands of years, evolutionarily, is nothing. It's not even small change. With the smallest tissue sample, any phylogeneticist could identify to genus the parent lineage of each SCP-1483 version no problem (assuming we've got DNA of an extant descendant of the common ancestor). Identification to species-level might be trickier if some groups radiated rapidly after arriving (quite possible, given the open niche space), so there could be new species in this time.

Unless of course  simply means these new lineages have all adapted in such incredibly bizarre ways that, although we know exactly what lines they came from, we don't have the ecological equivalent on Baseline Earth. Again, I don't think this is enough time for such radical changes in body form to occur.




附加记录：    

Homo heidelbergensis lived 0.6 – 0.35 million years ago, so again it seems the dates in the first quote are grossed underestimated, not to mention that I would say that makes the Baseline descendants of H. heidelbergensis obvious counterparts.




附加记录：    

Similar to the above: these programs will have to have been both very strict and have been going on for a very long time for the differences you list to have propogated through a large enough population to be stable sub-species. Of course, you did throw in the  but I'm unconvinced that something could suddenly engineer an entire hominid subspecies with exta arms and metallic body armor. Are they capable of successfully interbreeding? If we're using the biological species concept, they have to be to be subspecies. As a taxonomist, if I were given specimens of SCP-1483b-e, I would group them at the very least in separate genera. And all this change happened in the short span since H. heidelbergensis has been around?

edit: adopted/adapted typo. Also, descendent/descendant typo.





